            </rs>.</p>
               <p>The case was stated by Mr. Gurney.</p>
               <p>RICE PRICE. Q. You are an attorney - A. I am.</p>
               <p>Q. What is that you have got in your hand - A. The commission of bankruptcy against 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1650">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1650" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1650" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1650" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>Q. You are the attorney under the commission - A. We had it since the commission had been acted upon. We had it in our hands after the election of assignees.</p>
               <p>(The proceedings under the commission read.)</p>
               <p>Q. to Mr. Price. Turn to these proceedings and tell me, whether Nugent and Humphreys prove debts under that commission - 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1651">A. James Bond</persName>
             appears to have proved one hundred and thirty-eight pound, seven shillings and sixpence, for goods sold and delivered, and for money lent and advanced by the deponent to the bankrupt. John Folkard, on the second meeting on the 17th of February, 1812. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1652">
                  Jacob 
                  Grick
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1652" type="surname" value="Grick"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1652" type="given" value="Jacob"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1652" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             one hundred and fifty-nine pound, fourteen shillings, for goods sold by the deponent to the bankrupt. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1653">
                  Thomas 
                  Nugent
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1653" type="surname" value="Nugent"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1653" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1653" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , on the same day, one hundred and twenty-five pound, ten shillings, against the bankrupt, as acceptor of a bill of exchange, as described underneath, drawn by one 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1654">
                  John 
                  Scott Byerley
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1654" type="surname" value="Scott Byerley"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1654" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1654" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , the drawer of the bill.</p>
               <p>Q. How does it appear that 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1655">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1655" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1655" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1655" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             is indebted to 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1656">
                  Thomas 
                  Nugent
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1656" type="surname" value="Nugent"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1656" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1656" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - A. In as much as 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1657">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1657" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1657" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1657" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , is the acceptor of the bill, John Scott Byerley the drawer of the bill. Thomas Nugent, of Newport-market, gentleman, further saith, that 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1658">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1658" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1658" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1658" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             is still indebted to this deponent in the sum of one hundred and twenty-five pound, ten shillings, as described by this acceptance of a bill drawn by John Scott Byerley, endorsed 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1659">J. S. </persName>
            Byerley, accepted by the bankrupt. George Humphreys, he proves for the sum of one hundred and fourteen pound for goods sold and delivered by the deponent to John Folkard before he became a bankrupt.</p>
               <p>COURT. Does he describe the goods - A. No, he does not; all these debts are on the 15th of February; 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1660">
                  John 
                  Edward Kelly
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1660" type="surname" value="Edward Kelly"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1660" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1660" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , linen-draper, proves the sum of ninety-seven pounds, sixteen shillings, as the drawer of a bill of exchange, the consideration of the said bill was linen-drapery goods sold and delivered.</p>
               <p>Q. Who was the drawer of that bill - A. The drawer of that bill was the bankrupt, the acceptor was 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1661">
                  John 
                  Shehey
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1661" type="surname" value="Shehey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1661" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1661" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>Q.Before what commissioners does it appear that these several debts were proved - A. Before Mr. Burrow, Mr. Taunton, and Mr. Burrell.</p>
               <p>Q. Who were the assignees chosen that day - A. Mr. Powis, Mr. Hemmings, and Mr. Taylor.</p>
               <p>COURT. Who are the three that declared him a bankrupt - A. Mr. Morris, Mr. Taunton, and Mr. Burrell.</p>
               <p>MR. POWIS. I am a watch manufacturer; I live in Rosamon-street, Clerkenwell.</p>
               <p>Q. In the month of February last were you a creditor of 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1662">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1662" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1662" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1662" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            's; did you attend at the first public meeting of the commission - A. I did not. I did the second, at the time of the choice of assignees.</p>
               <p>Q. We have just learned that you, Mr. Hemmings, and Mr. Taylor, were chosen assignces - A. We were.</p>
               <p>Q. Was any attempt made to your choice for assignees - A. A very strong attempt. There was a gentleman I never saw before in my life, I understood his name was Brooks. Mr. Brooks was started for one, and Mr. Crouch, the petitioning creditor, for the other. These were the two persons that were started against me and the others. Mr. Crouch, I believe, married the bankrupt's sister.</p>
               <p>Q. As soon as you were chosen assignees, did you and the other assignees go to the bankrupt's house the same evening - A. We did not. On the next morning, the 18th, we went to the bankrupt's house in Great Surry-street, Black Friars-Road; Mr. Hemmings met me there. We took possession of the house.</p>
               <p>Q. When you took possession of the house, did you find the servant boy in possession of the business - A. We did not.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you find the maid-servant of the house - A. We did not. None of the servants of the bankrupt were left; they were gone.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you find the books - A. We did not.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you apply to the bankrupt, John, for his books - A. I had no opportunity of seeing the bankrupt till the third examination.</p>
               <p>Q. The third examination was the 28th of February, eleven days after, did you then apply to him for his<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181209160101"></xptr> books - A. When he appeared at Guildhall he appeared without his books. We asked him, where his books were. He said, they were in the neighbourhood; he himself had not the possession of them; that he had only possession of them a few days past. He had pawned them. He had five pounds lent upon them by a man of the name of Byerley.</p>
               <p>Q. Did he say at what time he had lodged them with Byerley - A. I do not recollect. I think he said he had got them that morning. He was ordered by the commissioner to fetch them. Mr. Mayhew (Mr. Price's partner) accompanied him. He came back with the books. The books are here.</p>
               <p>Q. Now, sir, in consequence of any suspicion you entertained, had you, before that, gone to the house of Mr. Bond, in Fleet-lane - A. I do not think I saw him until the third meeting. I am not certain.</p>
               <p>Q. I wish you would recollect - A. On the first private meeting, the 26th of February, Mr. Hemmings and I went to Bond's, in Fleet-lane. I am not satisfied as to the day. It was before the third meeting.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you go for the purpose of making enquiries respecting Bond and his debt - A. It happened that me and my brother assignee went together to Bond's, in Fleet-lane, to make enquiry respecting the debt, and to enquire how it arose.</p>
               <p>Q. Upon that occasion did you see a woman in the room whom you now know by the name of the Baroness Minkwitz - A. I did. At that time I did not know who she was. Nothing at that time past with her.</p>
               <p>Q. How soon after you had seen her at Bond's did she come to you and make a discovery - A. About two days after, she came to me and made some communication. I was alone.</p>
               <p>Q. Now, take into your hands the books of the bankrupt, and tell me whether you find certain names I am going to ask you about debitted for goods. Do you find Count Holmar debitted for any goods - A. Yes, I do. In folio 141, debitted three hundred and eleven pounds twelve shillings.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you find the Baroness Minkwitz debitted for any goods - A. I find her debitted for one hundred and forty-one pounds sixteen shillings.</p>
               <p>Q. On what articles is she debitted - A. Pearls, two gold watches. The whole debt is one hundred and forty one pounds sixteen shillings, and they give her a credit of eighty-two pounds, leaving a balance of fifty-nine pounds.</p>
               <p>Q. Now, sir, do you find Signora Moranda - A find her debitted for sixty pounds, and credited at - , leaving a balance of forty-nine pounds. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1663">
                  John 
                  Shehey
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1663" type="surname" value="Shehey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1663" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1663" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , I find, to him, two hundred and twenty-six pounds; his account balanced by bills. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1664">
                  William 
                  Halliday
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1664" type="surname" value="Halliday"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1664" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1664" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , three hundred and seventy-seven pounds debitted; his account balanced by bills. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1665">
                  Edward 
                  James
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1665" type="surname" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1665" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1665" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , two hundred and forty pounds seventeen shillings and eight pence. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1666">
                  Edward 
                  James
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1666" type="surname" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1666" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1666" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , no credit whatever.</p>
               <p>Q. Had you known by Baroness Minkwitz, before you were possessed of these books, that there were these debts - A. I was in possession of the books two or three days before, but I had sent them to my brother assignee.</p>
               <p>Q. Had she made any communication to you respecting them names - A. Yes, each of the names, excepting Halliday and Shehey she mentioned.</p>
               <p>Q. Now, sir, after you examined the books, did you make any enquiry of the bankrupt, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1667">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1667" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1667" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1667" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , who these several persons were - A. I did. I made the enquiry at my house repeatedly when he came.</p>
               <p>Q. Who did he tell you Countess Holmar was - A. He represented her being a woman he had long been acquainted with; a very good woman; that he had been induced to give her credit. I asked him when he first became acquainted with her. He said, she was introduced to him by the Baroness Minkwitz, who was also a creditor.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you ask him what the Count was - A. Yes; he gave me his address, Sloane-street; that she and her husband had removed from there; he did not know what had become of them; he believed they were gone out of the country. He was gone to take possession of an estate, or some property abroad. It was a very safe debt.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you enquire who the Baroness Minkwitz was - A. He said, he had known her for a length of time, but did not know what had become of her. Her debt appears to have been the day before the commission. On the 10th of January appears her debt.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you enquire who she was - A. She was an Opera dancer, or singer; she belonged to the Opera-house; he did not know where she now lived, but when he credited her she lived at No. 14, in the Haymarket. I applied at No. 14, in the Haymarket; they knew no such person. I asked him who 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1668">
                  John 
                  Shehey
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1668" type="surname" value="Shehey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1668" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1668" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was. He represented him having unfortunately, since he so credited him, gone into the Fleet.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1669">Q. William Halliday</persName>
            : did he tell you who he was - A. I had some knowledge of him myself; I questioned him on that account. He said, the first conversation he had with Halliday, he thought he was doing well; unfortunately he had gone into the Fleet a few days after he had credited him. Edward James; he said he knew nothing at all of him; he was recommended to him by the Baroness Menkwitz, and the only place he ever saw him was at the Black Lion, Wapping, independant of his own house.</p>

               <p>Q. Do you remember one day, when you were walking with 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1670">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1670" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1670" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1670" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , he being accosted by any person - A. Yes; that was the Baroness Minkwitz. They conversed together for a few minutes. I was with him. They conversed apart from me. She quitted him. I asked him who she was. He told me that she was a Miss Smith, an old friend and customer of his. I knew at that time who she was. At that time she had communicated to me, and I had communicated to my attorney.</p>
               <p>Q. In answer to a question that my learned friend put to you, that the bankrupt was examined by the commissioners privately - A. Yes, he was.</p>
               <p>Q. to Mr. Price. You have told us that you became solicitor to the commission after the second meeting - A. I did.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you attend at the private examinations - - A. I did, the whole of them. On the 30th of April, 1812, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1671">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1671" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1671" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1671" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             being sworn and examined<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181209160102"></xptr> before us, the major part of the commissioners, Mr. Burrow and Mr. Burrell, upon oath, saith, that the entry he made, one hundred and fourteen, ledger of bills, were given for washing. The credit side, goods sold to a person of the name of Moranda, was made up; about the time they were made the greater part were sold by my brother, James, to Signora Moranda. She is an Opera lady, and lives in the Haymarket. I believe her to be thirty years of age and upwards. The last articles were sold by myself. The entry, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1672">
                  Edward 
                  James
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1672" type="surname" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1672" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1672" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , was entered as a real transactions; and much about the same time they bear date, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1673">
                  Edward 
                  James
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1673" type="surname" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1673" type="given" value="Edward"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1673" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I do not think there are any regular entries made. He is about thirty years of age. The articles, seventy-three pounds, were taken away in an hackney coach, in day time. My brother, James, assisted in packing them up. They consisted of various articles of jewellery. Baroness Menkwitz lives in Downing-street. She actually owes me what appears in the books. When did you see the Baroness. In the early part of February I saw her at the West end of the town. She took the suit of pearls herself. All the goods in the said account were delivered to her in my shop. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1674">
                  John 
                  Shehey
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1674" type="surname" value="Shehey"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1674" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1674" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was a wine and brandy merchant in Smithfield. He came to my shop for the goods. He is now in the Fleet. The account of Count Holmar is a true and correct account. The goods sold in November last. I delivered them to him myself. The bullion consisted of doubloons, some India pieces, and some coin. The bullion was sold at different times. Halliday became a bankrupt in the Fleet. The goods were sold to Halliday when he lived in Bell Savage-yard, in the city. The eleventh leaf is written by the boy. The baroness is written by my brother, James.</p>

               <p>Q. to Mr. Powis. You have examined the books carefully - A. I have.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you ask him any questions about certain goods that he had charged, which you thought he had not rightly charged - A. I have asked him questions upon all these accompts which I suspected. I pointed out two accounts to him, and particular; Halliday was one, the other Shehey. I pointed out the absurdity, to shew him, that he could have credited such a man as Halliday; he must know his real situation in life. I remonstrated with him how he could have trusted such a man as that. At that time he trusted him he had been recently liberated from the Rules of the Fleet. At the time the bankrupt credited him, Halliday had no means of living. Speaking to him one time upon that, he said, you are the only man who knows any thing respecting Halliday or Shehey; if you remain quiet you shall have nothing to complain of. I told him, it would be better for him to tell the truth. After that he said, he believed the account of Halliday and Shehey to be fabricated, but said he, it was all his, William and Nugent's doing: he was ill at the time. He then told me, if I would remain his friend, and would not oppose his certificate, that he should have at command, in a short time, five or six thousand pounds. I said, why, you have not done the trick to deep as that, and asked him to explain himself. He said, he had it in his power to marry a woman of that property.</p>
               <p>Q. With respect to the enquiry of Bond; you have examined the books - A. I have.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you find any articles charged to these persons, which by these books you find to have come in afterwards - A. I do.</p>
               <p>Q. State the articles - A. It is in the account of James. The articles are two trunks booked to him in November last charged three pounds eight shillings. He said, he had them of Mr. Briant, Ludgate-hill. I pointed out to him the absurdity that he had not them in his possession until the 26th of that month. He said, it might be a mistake in the date. He was conscious the account of James was correct, although it was not his own making. He was ill a bed at the time.</p>
               <p>Q. Now, I ask you, sir, what is the deficiency upon the estate - A. The deficiency, admitting these debts to be just, amounts to between two and three thousand pounds, and if they are not just they amount to five.</p>
               <p>Mr. Andrews. What was the amount of your debt against 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1675">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1675" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
