                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1693" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             at that house.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you see Kelly there - A. Yes, and I heard a man called by the name of Shehey there. I gave 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1694">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1694" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1694" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1694" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             the blank acceptances. I said, I could not get any more. I left them all there, and I went home.</p>
               <p>Q. Where were they to go from thence - A. To Guildhall.</p>
               <p>COURT. Was it said so at that meeting - A. Yes, after I came home. Grick came home in about an hour after, and in the afternoon Nugent and 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1695">
                  James 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1695" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1695" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1695" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             called on me at my house. Nugent said, it is all over; we have lost the day. I did not know 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1696">
                  James 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1696" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1696" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1696" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             before. Nugent said, the money was all thrown away.</p>
               <p>Q. On the next day which of the parties did you see - A. James and 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1697">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1697" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1697" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1697" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . William Folkard said, as they had not got assignees they must make the books up, as they had not got their own friends for assignees. I turned to William, and did not wish to speak before this young man. He said, it was all right, it was his brother, James. He told me then he must put down that I owed so much money to John.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you owe the money - A. No. He told me he would call with Nugent and arrange it. James said, as you are the lady that has been in our shop I should have known you by the description of our young man.</p>
               <p>Q. Were you a prisoner at this time in the rules of the Fleet - A. I was not. I lodged in Fleet-lane. I paid six shillings a week.</p>
               <p>Q. Well, he said that Nugent and he would call and arrange it. Did Nugent afterwards call with William - A. Yes. He mentioned the Countess Holmar. I told him, she was gone abroad. He sold me he would be much obliged to me if I would find out when she went abroad, and when her husband went abroad.</p>
               <p>Q. Where had her husband been before she went abroad - A. In the King's Bench prison, and he would give half-a-crown to enquire when the Count left the King's Bench prison, to find out the exact day, and how he spelt his name. I sent Mr. Bond over. When Bond returned he gave me a bit of paper with something on it. I gave it to Nugent and 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1698">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1698" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1698" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1698" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I read it. It was the time when the Count left the King's Bench, and how he spelt his name.</p>
               <p>Q. Was any enquiry made where the Count lived - A. Yes. I told him she lived in Sloane-street, and the last time in Downing-street.</p>
               <p>Q. Were you acquainted with Madam Moranda - Yes, she was an opera singer. Nugent asked me what her name was. She had lodged with me when I lived in St. James's. Nugent had seen her there. I told him I did not know where she lived now. Folkard said, he would book her down some things that she owed him.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you mean owing him - A. No, his brother, John. I said, he might do it. I said, before you have been making fictitious bills, and now you are making debts. William said, they must make their accounts up.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you ask him why this was - A. Yes. I said, first you make people say you are indebted to them, and now you want people that do not owe you any thing, to put down that they do. He said, they must balance the accounts. After that, William came on a Monday. I said to William, are you going to think of me? What are you going to book me down. He said, I must book you down a handsome necklace, and other things. He said, if I wanted to go to the Opera, and wanted a necklace, I should have it lent me.</p>
               <p>Q. In the month of March do you recollect seeing any of them - A. Yes, I saw them all very often. 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1699">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1699" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1699" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1699" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             called on me one morning. Mr. Grick was with me. He asked me if I had seen Nugent. I told him, no, not this morning. He said, he wanted some money, if I knew where to get him some. He took out some strings of pearls. I asked him, how much he wanted on them. I saw a necklace. I said, is that necklace put down to me. He said, he did not know, I must ask his brother, John.</p>
               <p>Q. Look at them writings, and tell me whether you know the hand-writing; they are two letters: who wrote them - 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1700">A. John Folkard</persName>
            : I saw him write them in Mr. Bond's parlour, and both at the same time. Mrs. and Mr. Bond, and Mr. Grick, were there at the time.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you see them papers - A. Yes; they were written at the same time the letters were. They are purporting to be bills of Bond, and Grick, and myself. They were written by 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1701">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1701" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1701" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1701" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , in the presence of Bond, and his wife, and Grick, in Bond's house.</p>
               <p>Q. Before these letters were written had you seen the assignees - A. Yes; they had been repeatedly to Bond, and threatened him to take him up, unless Bond could account how the debt accrued. The assignees did not know me then.</p>
               <p>COURT. Were these letters written after the assignees threatened to take up Bond - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. Whose hand-writing are they - 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1702">A. John Folkard</persName>
            's.</p>
               <p>Mr. Knapp. Did you ever give the account that you have to day until the assigness threatened to take up Bond - A. No.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you apprehend, yourself, that any ill consequence would happen to you if you did not make that confession - A. I told 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1703">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1703" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1703" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1703" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             that he must come and appease the assigness; unless he would tell the truth I would.</p>
               <p>Q. How long have you been in England - A. Twenty years.</p>
               <p>Q. Your husband has been sent out of the country as an alien - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. You came here in custody - A. Yes, and I am to be sent out of the country as an alien.</p>
               <p>Q. Have you been in custody - A. Yes, I have been in the Fleet.</p>
               <p>Q. When was the first time that the assignees applied to you - A. The assignees never applied to me. I told Mr. Powis, myself, the truth.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181209160105"></xptr> 
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1704">
                  GEORGE 
                  PREEST
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1704" type="surname" value="PREEST"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1704" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1704" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. Where do you live - A. No. 20, High-street, Bloomsbury-market.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you remember the Baroness Minkwitz making any application to you in February last - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. Did she produce to you any paper - A. Yes, a blank stamp. I did not see any hand-writing at all on it. It laid on the table. She wanted me to go in a coach with her to a person in the Surry-road, to draw upon him for a sum of money.</p>
               <p>Q. Did she mention the name - A. I cannot say that she did. She wanted me to go. I immediately refused. and she went away.</p>
               <p>Mr. Andrews. Had you known her before - A.Yes; I was in a lock-up-house with her.</p>
               <p>JAMES BOND. Q. In the month of February last where did you live - A. At 21, Fleet-lane. I am, what is called in our trade, a boot-foot-maker. I work for shops. The Baroness Menkwitz lodged in my house.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you remember, in February last, the Baroness making any application to you respecting going to Guildhall - A. She did.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you understand that some application was made for that purpose on the Sunday - A. I did.</p>
               <p>Q. What time did you go out - A. About half past ten o'clock, or later.</p>
               <p>Q. Upon your coming home together was any thing given to her - A. Yes, by the servant girl; there was a note, and shortly after that Thomas Nugent, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1705">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1705" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1705" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1705" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , and 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1706">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1706" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1706" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1706" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             came, and went into the one pair room, which was occupied by the Baroness.</p>

               <p>Q. After they had gone up did any body come down to you - A. I cannot positively say. I rather think Nugent did, and I was asked, would I undertake to take a bill, and present it at Guildhall the following day.</p>
               <p>Q. For what purpose - A. There was no specific purpose mentioned to me. I was to take the bill, and present it to persons at Guildhall. I did not enquire. It was a business I had no knowledge of at that time. I understood then that John Folkard was a bankrupt.</p>
               <p>Q. Was any thing offered you - A. That I should be paid for my days work, and to have a dinner. I was to receive a pound note.</p>
               <p>Q. Was Grick in your house - A. Yes, part of the time.</p>
               <p>Q. While you were in the room was any thing written - A. There was the bill that I had, was written, and I believe another. The other was for Grick. I never saw the Folkards before that time.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1707">
                  JOHN 
                  DAVID
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1707" type="surname" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1707" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1707" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             KELLLY. Q.You are clerk to Mr. Harmer. Did you serve a copy of that notice on the prisoner, Nugent - A. On Nugent, and on the Folkards, and their two attorneys.</p>
               <p>(Read.)</p>
               <p>Q. to Mr. Bond. Did you sign your name to the bill as drawer - A. I did.</p>
               <p>Q. Was your bill accepted by 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1708">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1708" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1708" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1708" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             - A. It was accepted by 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1709">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1709" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1709" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1709" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I did not see him write it. There was an appointment made to meet at Butler's Head, Bell-alley, in Coleman-street. I went there the next day. I believe I went there by myself, others followed. When I got there I saw a person of the name of Shehey. From there we adjourned to the White Bear. I cannot say that Shehey was there. We went to the White Bear, London Wall. I saw 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1710">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1710" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1710" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1710" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            , Nugent, and Kelly, and a many others. I cannot say particularly whom: there was a number. The first thing that we thought of was, to provide something to eat. I went to Guildhall with Grick. There I saw the same persons as I saw at the White Bear. We did not all go together. I saw 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1711">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1711" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1711" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1711" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             there, not John. I saw 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1712">
                  William 
                  Kelly
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1712" type="surname" value="Kelly"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1712" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1712" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             and Grick there. I believe I saw Humphreys there.</p>
               <p>Q. Did you see Humpreys at the White Bear before you went to Guildhall - A. I think he was there. When I got to Guildhall, I proved my bill, and Grick did, and Kelly, and others did, as far as I saw. When I returned to the White Bear, I gave back the note I had received of Nugent. He called me out into another room. I there gave it him.</p>
               <p>Q. After that did you tell 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1713">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1713" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1713" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1713" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             that Mr. Powis, the assignee, had called upon you - A. I did. Upon that 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1714">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1714" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1714" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1714" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             wrote this bill for me. I was to give this bill to Mr. Powis.</p>
               <p>(Bill read.)</p>
               <p>Q. Had you ever fold 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1715">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1715" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1715" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1715" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             any shoes or boots, as specified in that bill - A. No, I had not.</p>
               <p>Q. Who was present at the time he wrote that account - A. I believe the Baroness was, and Grick, and this letter was written at the same time, to shew Mr. Powis.</p>
               <p>(Letter read.)</p>
               <p>Mr. Knapp. What are you - A. A boot-foot-maker.</p>
               <p>Q. A housekeeper - A. I was at that time.</p>
               <p>Q. And at this time, knowing yourself to much distressed, you went to Guildhall; you had no thought of committing perjury - A. I do not say but what I committed perjury.</p>
               <p>Q. Which is the truth; that which you chose to swear before this - A. What I have said now is the truth.</p>
               <p>Q. You were taken up, were you not - A. No, I was only threatened to be taken up.</p>
               <p>Q. Then you turned cat in pan, and gave this account to save yourself.</p>
               <p>Q. What was the rent that the Baroness paid you - A. She was to pay me the rent of the house, if I would let her carry on the business of selling coals. On her being taken up I lost five months rent, which was fourteen shillings and sixpence a week.</p>
               <p>Q. You were quite ruined - A. I was.</p>
               <p>COURT. You, in consequence of your losing five months rent, which was fourteen shillings and sixpence a week, you were quite ruined - A. I was.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1716">
                  JACOB 
                  GRICK
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1716" type="surname" value="GRICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1716" type="given" value="JACOB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1716" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. In the month of February last where did you live - A. In Fleet-lane, at Mr. Bond's.</p>
               <p>Q. What are you by business - A. I was formerly a clerk. I was then living in the rules of the Fleet to avoid being arrested.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you remember being in Baroness Menkwitz's room when Nugent called there - A. I recollect<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181209160106"></xptr> his calling there in the month of February. He first talked privately to her. I heard my name mentioned between them; then Nugent mentioned a bankruptcy of 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1717">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1717" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1717" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1717" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; that he had spent a good deal of money; they wished for friends to get him through. Nugent wished me to take a bill, to go to Guildhall with, to prove under the bankruptcy, to get him through. He said he would pay me for my trouble. At last I agreed to do it. He appointed to meet me on the Sunday. I went out to avoid it, and when I came home I saw the two Folkards and Nugent in the room with Bond.</p>
               <p>Q. Were any stamps produced, and bills drawn - A. Yes; William Folkard produced them; some 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1718">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1718" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
