               <p>Q. to Grick. Had you ever sold him any bullion - A. No, I was as poor as a man could be. Two or three days after we had been to Guildhall, 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1726">
                  John 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1726" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1726" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1726" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             came to the Baroness, and enquired after names of persons that the Baroness knew; they wished to have some names of the Baroness's friends to book debts down to. They enquired after Signor Moranda, Count Holmar, and another Baron. They wished to have debts booked to them to make the books up. They said, they were to be persons that had gone out of the country. Nugent and Folkard said so. They called some one after upon the Baroness, and produced a necklace. They asked the Baroness, where they could pledge them. She recommended them to Parker's, in Fleet-street.</p>
               <p>Q. Last night did you come to the house of Mr. Harmer for the purpose of giving information - A. I did. I met 
               <persName id="t18120916-214-person1727">
                  William 
                  Folkard
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1727" type="surname" value="Folkard"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1727" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1727" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             in Fetter-lane. He asked me how I did. I told him the time was coming on. He asked me whether I was subpoened. I said, yes; I was very sorry for it. He asked me to go to Mr. Morley, the attorney, in Fleet-market.</p>
               <p>Mr. Andrews. Who was your master when you were a clerk - A. Messrs. Hoffman and Co. of the Crescent, in the Minories.</p>
               <p>Q. When you lived in Bond's house how many rooms did you and the Baroness occupy - A. There were two bed rooms between us.</p>
               <p>Q. When the Baroness walked Fleet-street did you accompany her - A. I do not understand you.</p>
               <p>Q.How long did you live together - A. Not quite a year.</p>
               <p>Q. Are you friends now - A. We are not. I intend to go abroad of my own will. I certainly dislike her.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1728">
                  HANNAH 
                  BALDWIN
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1728" type="surname" value="BALDWIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1728" type="given" value="HANNAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1728" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . Q. You keep the White Bear, London-wall - A. Yes.</p>
               <p>Q. Do you remember on Monday, in February last, any persons being at your house - A. I do. I recollect my husband being ill at that time. Bond came and asked me if I had any room to accommodate them for refreshment. There were there four or five men. I noticed none.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18120916-214-person1729">
                  SARAH 
                  WARNECK
               <interp inst="t18120916-214-person1729" type="surname" value="WARNECK"></interp>
